About the company

Bellabeat is a small high-tech company that manufactures health-focused smart products for women. It was founded in 2013 by UrÅ¡ka SrÅ¡en and Sando Mur. Bellabeat products collect data on activity, sleep, stress, and reproductive health. Products include a Bellabeat app, wellness trackers, smart-technology water bottle, and a subscription-based membership. Their products are sold by online retailers and on their own website. Their marketing strategy primarily focuses on digital marketing (Google Search, Facebook, Insta, Twitterâ¦), but they invested in traditional ads too (radio, TV, print, billboardsâ¦).

Key stakeholders

  • UrÅ¡ka SrÅ¡en: co-founder and CCO
  • Sando Mur: co-founder, key executive team member
  • Bellabeat marketing analytics team

Business task and questions

Identifying trends and connections in smart device usage by analyzing usersâ fitness and health data collected by non-Bellabeat smart devices, in order to help improve the companyâs marketing strategy. In my analysis, Iâll try to answer the following questions:

    1. What are some trends in smart device usage?
    1. How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?
    1. How could these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing strategy?

PREPARE

The Data

Data source: FitBit Fitness Tracker Data, CC0: Public Domain updated by user Mobius

  • Citation: Furberg, R., Brinton, J., Keating, M., & Ortiz, A. (2016). Crowd-sourced Fitbit datasets 03.12.2016-05.12.2016 [Data set]. Zenodo. https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.53894

  • 28 datasets were generated by respondents to a distributed survey via Amazon Mechanical Turk between 12/03/2016-12/05/2016.

  • 33 eligible Fitbit users consented to the submission of personal tracker data, including minute-level output for physical activity, heart rate, and sleep monitoring. The recorded data is anonymous, and there is no data indicating the identity of the users.

  • In my analysis, I use the data from 12/04/2016 to 12/05/2016. After downloading the folder from Kaggle, I stored it on my computer, in a separate folder.

  • The database contains 18 .csv files. The majority of the data is in a long format, and every table has a unique âIDâ column which can be used as a primary key to connect the tables. The data represents quantitative metrics like heart rate, steps or sleep time, broken down into minutes, hours, days and merged data.

Data limitations

  • Given the small sample size and the lack of demographic data about the users, the data could be biased, and not represent the broader population. In the absence of demographic data, our analysis regarding the users themselves will be limited.
  • The data was collected in 2016, making it possibly outdated.
  • Some datasets include metrics and labels that lack clear definitions (e.g.Â column âvalueâ in minuteSleep_merged.csv), making it challenging for external viewers to interpret their meaning accurately. The Fitabase Data Dictionary can be found online that helps to interpret the data values.

Splitting the date and time, correcting the data type, and adding the weekdays column:

date <- mdy(daily_activity$activity_date)
daily_activity <- daily_activity %>% 
  mutate(daily_activity, activity_date = date) %>% 
  rename(date = activity_date) %>% 
  mutate(weekdays = weekdays(date))

minute_sleep <- minute_sleep %>% 
  mutate(
    day = as.Date(date, format = "%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p"), #extracts the date
    time = format(as.POSIXct(date, format = "%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p"), format = "%H:%M:%S") #extracts the time but in character type
  ) %>% 
  select(-date) #hides the original activity_minute column
minute_sleep$time <- hms::as_hms(minute_sleep$time) #converts the time from character to numerical

daily_sleep <- daily_sleep %>% 
  mutate(
    date = as.Date(sleep_day, format = "%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p")) %>%  #extracts the date
  select(-sleep_day) %>% #hides the original sleep_day column
  mutate(weekdays = weekdays(date)) %>% 
  select(id, date, weekdays, total_minutes_asleep, total_time_in_bed) # reorders the columns

hour_intensity <- hour_intensity %>% 
  mutate(
    date = as.Date(activity_hour, format = "%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p"), #extracts the date
    time = format(as.POSIXct(activity_hour, format = "%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p"), format = "%H:%M:%S") #extracts the time but in character type
  ) %>% 
  select(-activity_hour) #hides the original activity_minute column
hour_intensity$time <- hms::as_hms(hour_intensity$time) #converts the time from character to numerical

ANALYSE AND SHARE

I will create a few summary dataframes. As the quick summary statistics showed, in some cases the difference between the mean and the median is pretty significant. Therefore I chose to use the median in my calculations, in order to get a more accurate representation.

Intensity summary

First, letâs see the daily intensity values. The column âtotal_intensityâ in the âhourly_intensityâ dataframe is a value calculated by adding all the minute-level intensity values that occurred within the hour. The minute-level intensity values are: 0 = Sedentary, 1 = Light, 2 = Moderate, 3 = Very Active. The column âaverage_intensityâ is the âtotal_intensityâ for that âactivity_hourâ, divided by 60. Iâll use this value as the intensity score in my calculations. Iâll also create a dataframe for the monthly intensity values and the distribution by weekdays.

daily_intensity <- hour_intensity %>% 
  group_by(id, date) %>% 
  summarise(total_daily_intensity = sum(total_intensity),
            daily_intensity_score = median(average_intensity, na.rm=T)) %>%
  mutate(weekdays = weekdays(date))

monthly_intensity <- daily_intensity %>% 
  group_by(id) %>% 
  summarize(med_monthly_intensity_score = median(daily_intensity_score, na.rm=T))

intensity_weekdays <- daily_intensity %>% 
  group_by(weekdays) %>% 
  summarize(med_weekday_intensity_score = median(daily_intensity_score)) %>% # the median of the active daily values compared to 24 hrs
  mutate(weekdays = factor(weekdays, levels = c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"))) %>% 
  arrange(weekdays)

Activity summary

Letâs summarize the activity data. I merged the sleep and intensity data into the daily_activity dataframe, so it makes a comprehensive overview. I also filtered out data points with 0 calories burned a day - after checking them, they were 24 hours sedentary minutes only, skewing the data.

daily_activity <- daily_activity %>% 
  mutate(total_daily_active_hours = ((very_active_minutes + fairly_active_minutes + lightly_active_minutes)/60)) %>% 
  filter(calories > 0) %>% 
  left_join(daily_sleep %>% select(id, date, total_minutes_asleep), by = c("id", "date")) %>% 
  left_join(daily_intensity %>% select(id, date, daily_intensity_score), by = c("id", "date"))

monthly_activity <- daily_activity %>% 
  group_by(id) %>% 
  summarize(
    total_days = n(),
    total_active_hrs = sum(very_active_minutes+fairly_active_minutes+lightly_active_minutes)/60,
    med_active_hrsperday = median((very_active_minutes+fairly_active_minutes+lightly_active_minutes)/60),
    total_sedentary_hrs = sum(sedentary_minutes)/60,
    med_sedentary_hrsperday = median((sedentary_minutes)/60),
    med_sleep_hrsperday = median((total_minutes_asleep)/60, na.rm=T),
    med_monthly_intensity = median(daily_intensity_score, na.rm=T),
    total_cals = sum(calories)) %>% 
  left_join(monthly_sleep %>% select(id, number_of_nights), by = "id") 

active_weekdays <- daily_activity %>% 
  group_by(weekdays) %>% 
  summarize(med_activity_hrsperday = median((very_active_minutes+fairly_active_minutes+lightly_active_minutes)/60)) %>% 
  mutate(weekdays = factor(weekdays, levels = c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"))) %>% 
  arrange(weekdays)

I couldnât find information whether the sleeping time in also included in the sedentary minutes. After analyzing the data, I couldnât find convincing evidence either. After adding all the activity minutes, the sedentary minutes and the sleeping minutes, one should get 1440 minutes (= 24 hours). But in many instances, the sum would be greater than 1440. My guess would be that some Fitbit devices are better at differentiating between sedentary time and sleeping than others. This leaves us with unreliable data about sedentary time, therefore Iâll not include them in my final reports.

Plots

First, letâs see the distribution of activity time/day.

ggplot(daily_activity, aes(x = total_daily_active_hours)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), fill = "lightgreen", color = "darkgreen", binwidth = 0.5) +
  geom_density(color = "red", linewidth = 1) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 9, by = 0.5)) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = median(total_daily_active_hours)), color = "blue3", size = 1) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = mean(total_daily_active_hours)), color = "violetred1", size = 1) +
  geom_text(aes(x = median(total_daily_active_hours), y = 0.24, label = "Median"), 
            color = "blue3", size = 4, angle = 0, vjust = -0.5, hjust = 0) +
  geom_text(aes(x = mean(total_daily_active_hours), y = 0.24, label = "Mean"), 
            color = "violetred1", size = 4, angle = 0, vjust = -0.5, hjust = 1) +
  labs(title = "The distribution of active hours per day",
       x = "Active hours/day",
       caption = "Data from 12/04/2016 to 12/05/2016")

The histogram suggests a positively skewed distribution, meaning most users have lower daily active hours, and fewer users are active for longer durations. The median active hours per day is around 4 hours, as indicated by the vertical blue line. This means half the users have active hours below 4 hours per day, and half are above. The mean is also around 4 hours, a bit below the median - which is unusual for a right-skewed distribution. There is a noticeable drop-off in density after the peak around 4-5.5 active hours per day, with very few users having more than 6-7 hours of active time. Thereâs a great number of users with 0 hours of activity but still having calories burnt (since we filtered out users with zero burnt calories from the dataframe). The column âcaloriesâ is the total estimated energy expenditure. The estimated energy expenditure takes into account the userâs basal metabolic rate, the activity recorded by the device, and any manually logged activities. This makes it possible to have zero active time but still having burnt calories.

As the plot shows, the week usually starts strong, with higher activity and less sleep. By Wednesday, users tend to get tired, as their sleep increases and active hours decrease. While the active hours remain low, sleep hours also hit rock bottom on Friday - I assume itâs due to typical Friday night activities like socializing and winding down after the work week. Saturday is the second most active day, and sleep also increases - users seem to have more time during the weekend for these activities. Sunday on the other hand is all about resting with the highest sleeping hours and lowest active hours. Keeping in mind this weekly pattern can be useful when planning the companyâs marketing strategy.

Letâs see the sleep quality by examining the sleep values measured by the devices during the sleeping hours. The devices assigned a value to every sleeping minute. According to the Fitabase Data Dictionary, the values mean: 1 = asleep, 2 = restless, 3 = awake. First, Iâll count the number of each value occurring in the dataframe, and calculate the percentages. Then Iâll create a pie chart displaying the share of each value.

sleep_value <- minute_sleep %>% 
  group_by(value) %>% 
  summarize(count = n()) %>% 
  mutate(percentage = count/sum(count) * 100,
         label = paste0(c("1 = Asleep", "2 = Restless", "3 = Awake")[value],
                        " (", round(percentage, 1), "%)"))

ggplot(sleep_value, aes(x = "", y = count, fill = factor(value))) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 1) +
  coord_polar("y") +
  scale_fill_manual(

       subtitle = "The share of the sleep values of every user",
       fill = "Sleep value",
       caption = "Data from 12/04/2016 to 12/05/2016, from 24 users.") +
  theme_void()

Itâs difficult to interpret these values as Fitbit doesnât provide any explanation on how these values are measured, and whatâs their definition. However, the values cannot be matched with the sleep stages recognized by the Sleep Foundation. Without more context on the methodology, it is challenging to assess the accuracy or meaning of these specific sleep quality metrics.

The correlation coefficient between the total active hours and median active hours is 0.88464440, indicating a strong positive relationship. Users generally maintain a steady and consistent level of activity throughout the month. In terms of intensity, the most active users tend to have the highest intensity levels - similarly, users with higher median active hours but with slightly lower total active hours also have high intensity levels.

ACT

What are some trends in smart device usage?

The sample size of 33 users was insufficient to draw broad or definitive conclusions. Additionally, several datasets included even fewer participants (e.g.Â the sleep datasets had 24 participants, the weight dataset had 8 participants), many of whom did not log their data consistently on a daily basis. Key gaps were observed in the logging of sleep and weight data, which limits the reliability of the analysis. A significant challenge was the lack of transparency regarding Fitbitâs measurement methods. While itâs reasonable for the company to keep these methods confidential, this created obstacles in analyzing certain datasets â particularly when distinguishing between sedentary and sleeping minutes. This lack of clarity limited the depth and reliability of the insights that could be drawn from the data.

How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?

Bellabeat users may also face similar inconsistencies in device usage and data logging. Addressing these issues should be a priority to ensure reliable data for analysis. Potential next steps include:

  • Investigating the reasons behind inconsistent data logging.

  • Improving the logging process through user feedback, technical updates, or campaigns encouraging more accurate and consistent data entry.

Additionally, a notable gap in the dataset is the absence of reproductive health data. Bellabeat, as a company focused on womenâs health, could greatly benefit from exploring usage trends related to reproductive health. Such insights could inform the development of new, women-centric features and products that cater directly to their target audience.

How could these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing strategy?

  • Gamification and incentives: Introduce personalized reminders, weekly challenges, and leaderboards to encourage consistent device usage. Offer prizes, such as discount coupons, for top performers.
  • Partnerships: Collaborate with sportswear brands, dietitians, or fitness trainers. Joint campaigns and exclusive offers can increase activity levels and strengthen brand positioning.
  • Personalization: Provide users with a customized app interface, personal avatars, and badges. Use their activity and sleep data to deliver tailored recommendations, such as workout plans or guided meditations.
  • Data quality control: Implement systems to detect inconsistent logging early on and prompt users with reminders or notifications. Allow data edits to correct inaccuracies.
  • Focus on women: Emphasize Bellabeatâs commitment to womenâs health. Expand the product line to include not only smart devices but also clothing, accessories, fitness equipment, or professional services like consultations with personal trainers and dietitians.

Conclusion

To improve user experience and reliability of data insights, Bellabeat should address challenges with inconsistent logging and expand their offerings to cater more specifically to womenâs health needs. By leveraging personalized engagement strategies and focusing on empowering women through innovative products, Bellabeat can enhance its market presence while staying true to its core mission.
